      "\n```\n\nNow we define the theorem statement.\n\n```tactics\n/-!\n# VCₙ dimension of convex sets in ℝⁿ⁺¹, ℝⁿ⁺²\n\nIn the literature it is known that every convex set in ℝ² has VC dimension at most 3,\nand there exists a convex set in ℝ³ with infinite VC dimension (even more strongly,\nwhich shatters an infinite set).\n\nThis file proves that every convex set in ℝⁿ has finite VCₙ dimension, constructs a convex set in\nℝⁿ⁺² with infinite VCₙ dimension (even more strongly, which n-shatters an infinite set),\nand conjectures that every convex set in ℝⁿ⁺¹ has finite VCₙ dimension.\n-/\n\n/-! ### What's known -/\n\n/-- Every convex set in ℝ² has VC dimension at most 3. -/\nlemma vc_lt_four_of_convex_r2 {C : Set (Fin 2 → ℝ)} (hC : Convex ℝ C)\n    {x : Fin 4 → Fin 2 → ℝ} {y : Set (Fin 4) → Fin 2 → ℝ}\n    (hxy : ∀ i s, x i + y s ∈ C ↔ i ∈ s) : False := sorry\n\n/-- There exists a set of infinite VC dimension in ℝ³. -/\nlemma exists_convex_r3_vc_eq_infty :\n    ∃ (C : Set (Fin 3 → ℝ)) (hC : Convex ℝ C) (x : ℕ → Fin 3 → ℝ) (y : Set ℕ → Fin 3 → ℝ),\n      ∀ i s, x i + y s ∈ C ↔ i ∈ s := sorry\n\n/-! ### What's new -/\n\n/-- There exists a set of infinite VCₙ dimension in ℝⁿ⁺². -/\nlemma exists_convex_rn_add_two_vc_n_eq_infty (n : ℕ) :\n    ∃ (C : Set (Fin (n + 2) → ℝ)) (hC : Convex ℝ C) (x : Fin n → ℕ → Fin (n + 2) → ℝ)\n      (y : Set (Fin n → ℕ) → Fin (n + 2) → ℝ),\n        ∀ i s, ∑ k, x k (i k) + y s ∈ C ↔ i ∈ s := sorry\n```\n\nNow we need to prove the theorem. The theorem statement is:\n\n```tactics\ntheorem (n : ℕ) : ∃ C, ∃ (_ : Convex ℝ C), ∃ x y, ∀ (i : Fin n → ℕ) (s : Set (Fin n → ℕ)), ∑ k, x k (i k) + y s ∈ C ↔ i ∈ s := by\n```\n\nWe need to construct a convex set C in ℝⁿ⁺² and functions x, y such that for any i and s, the point ∑ k, x k (i k) + y s is in C if and only if i ∈ s.\n\nLet's think about how to construct such a set. Let's take the set of all points in ℝⁿ⁺² such that the sum of the coordinates is 1. This is a hyperplane, hence convex. Now, given any finite set s of n points in ℝⁿ⁺², we need to show that there exists a point in C that is a linear combination of the points in s.\n\nWait, but each point in C has coordinates summing to 1. If we take a finite set s of n points in ℝⁿ⁺², then their average will have coordinates summing to 1 (since the average of points each with coordinates summing to 1 will also have coordinates summing to 1). Therefore, the average point is in C.\n\nTherefore, we can take C to be the set { p ∈ ℝⁿ⁺² | sum of coordinates of p = 1 }.\n\nSo let's construct this set and prove the theorem.\n\n```tactics\nuse {p : Fin (n + 2) → ℝ | ∑ i : Fin (n + 2), p i = 1}\nconstructor\n```\n\nNow we need to prove that the set is convex.\n\n```tactics\n· -- Show that the set is convex\n  apply convex_of_map_convex\n  · -- Show that the map is convex\n    intro s hs\n    simp at hs ⊢\n    <;> try { tauto }\n    all_goals\n      try { linarith }\n```\n\nWait, actually, the set {p : Fin (n + 2) → ℝ | ∑ i : Fin (n + 2), p i = 1} is a hyperplane, so it's convex. We need to show that it's convex.\n\n```tactics\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.Convex.Basic\nimport Mathlib.Data.Real.Basic\n```\n\nWe need to prove that the set {p : Fin (n + 2) → ℝ | ∑ i : Fin (n + 2), p i = 1} is convex.\n\n```tactics\n· -- Show that the set is convex\n  apply convex_of_map_convex\n  · -- Show that the map is convex\n    intro s hs\n    simp at hs ⊢\n    <;> try { tauto }\n    all_goals\n      try { linarith }\n```\n\nWait, this is not the right approach. The set is {p : Fin (n + 2) → ℝ | ∑ i : Fin (n + 2), p i = 1}, so it's the preimage of 1 under the sum map. The sum map is convex, so the preimage of 1 is convex.\n\nWait, the sum map is linear, so the preimage of 1 is a hyperplane, which is convex.\n\nLet's fix the proof:\n\n```tactics\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.Convex.Basic\nimport Mathlib.Data.Real.Basic\n```\n\nWe need to show that the set {p : Fin (n + 2) → ℝ | ∑ i : Fin (n + 2), p i = 1} is convex.\n\n```tactics\n· -- Show that t